    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 6, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🐲 DeepSeek V4: One Trillion Parameters, $5.2 Million, Fully Open\n\nChina released a frontier-class AI model and the training cost was less than a studio apartment in San Francisco.\n\n- **The model:** DeepSeek V4 — 1T parameter Mixture-of-Experts, open weights, native multimodal (text, image, video), 1M-token context window, optimized for Chinese domestic chips. Benchmark performance: competitive with Claude Opus 4.6.\n- **The price:** US labs spend hundreds of millions to train comparable models. DeepSeek reportedly did this for $5.2M, released simultaneously with Tencent's new Hunyuan model.\n\n*America spent a decade arguing that export controls would keep frontier AI in US hands. DeepSeek V4 is fully open-weight and costs less than a Super Bowl ad.*\n\n**Sources:** [NxCode](https://www.nxcode.io/resources/news/deepseek-v4-release-specs-benchmarks-2026) | [Dataconomy](https://dataconomy.com/2026/03/16/deepseek-v4-and-tencents-new-hunyuan-model-to-launch-in-april/)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 Figure's CEO Says Humanoids Are Real This Year\n\nThe CEO of Figure AI has announced that 2026 is the year humanoid robots stop being a PowerPoint and start being a product.\n\n- **The prediction:** Figure CEO Brett Adcock forecast commercial humanoid robots and eVTOLs crossing from demonstration into deployment in 2026, driven by memory AI and embodied intelligence advances.\n- **The market:** The AI robotics sector is projected at $375.8B by 2035 at 17.33% CAGR. Investor confidence is accelerating as multiple humanoid platforms report their first real-world deployments this quarter.\n\n*Bold claim. Very bold. Also the same bold claim made in 2023, 2024, and 2025.*\n\n**Sources:** [Interesting Engineering](https://interestingengineering.com/ai-robotics/science-fiction-become-reality-in-2026) | [Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/04/04/prediction-ai-robotics-will-be-a-375-billion-indus/)\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 AI Hits 95% Accuracy in Parkinson's, 92.5% in Alzheimer's\n\nMedical AI had a quietly significant week while everyone was watching the chatbot benchmarks.\n\n- **The milestones:** A multimodal AI system achieved 95% accuracy in Parkinson's disease management and 92.5% in early Alzheimer's diagnosis, per the Weekly Health & AI Digest.\n- **The context:** NHS England simultaneously issued new guidelines on AI-powered ambient scribes in hospital settings. Clinical-grade AI is arriving less dramatically than expected — through regulatory frameworks and accuracy benchmarks, not press releases.\n\n*The AI systems quietly approaching medical-grade accuracy don't have marketing teams. Which is actually kind of comforting.*\n\n**Sources:** [Yesil Science](https://yesilscience.com/weekly-health-ai-digest-april-06-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## ⚖️ California's AI Executive Order Is the Closest Thing America Has to AI Law\n\nGovernor Newsom signed an executive order this week that, by virtue of California's market size, will function as national AI policy whether the rest of the country likes it or not.\n\n- **What it requires:** AI companies doing business with California must disclose policies on illegal content distribution, model bias, and civil rights violations. The Trump White House is actively trying to preempt state AI rules.\n- **The dynamic:** California regulates. Tech companies comply nationally because inconsistent state-by-state implementations cost more than just meeting the strictest standard. This is how GDPR started.\n\n*The federal government decided not to regulate AI. California will now regulate AI for America. (Nobody could have predicted this.)*\n\n**Sources:** [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/04/03/california-national-testing-ground-ai-rules)\n\n---\n\n## 🔓 AI Is Making Crypto Theft Cheaper. The Ledger CTO Is Not Happy.\n\nLedger's CTO issued a warning this week: AI tools are dramatically lowering the expertise barrier for crypto attacks, and $1.4 billion in losses from the past year suggest the barrier wasn't high enough to begin with.\n\n- **What's happening:** AI is being used to find vulnerabilities, automate phishing, and bypass security layers at scale. Attack sophistication is increasing faster than defense infrastructure.\n- **The number:** $1.4B in hacks and exploits over the past year. For context, that's more than the GDP of several small nations — lost to increasingly automated theft.\n\n*The crypto industry spent years arguing that blockchain was inherently secure. AI would like to negotiate.*\n\n**Sources:** [CoinDesk](https://www.coindesk.com/tech/2026/04/05/ai-is-making-crypto-s-security-problem-even-worse-ledger-cto-warns)"
